Question (2)

boxplot(salary~sex,data = Salaries,xlab = "Sex",ylab = "Salary",main="Salaries Distribution by Sex")

with(Salaries,by(salary,sex,median))
## sex: Female
## [1] 103750
## ------------------------------------------------------------ 
## sex: Male
## [1] 108043
with(Salaries,by(salary,sex,mean))
## sex: Female
## [1] 101002.4
## ------------------------------------------------------------ 
## sex: Male
## [1] 115090.4

The medians of male and female salaries are very closed, but the means of male and female salaries are obviously different.

Use Wilcoxon test to do significance test. In this case, we dont have to known the exact distribution of salary by sex.

H0:There is no statistically significant difference between female and male salaries.

H1:There is statistically significant difference between female and male salaries.

wilcox.test(salary~sex,data = Salaries,conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  salary by sex
## W = 5182.5, p-value = 0.008237
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

p-value<0.05, so we can reject H0 at 95% confidence interval. There is statistically significant difference between female and male salaries!

In this question , I classify salary by rank into 6 categories.

mystats<-function(x){
  m<-mean(x)
  n<-length(x)
  s<-sd(x)
  skew<-sum((x-m)^3/s^3)/n
  kurt<-sum((x-m)^4/s^4)/n-3
  return(c(n=n,mean=m,stdev=s,skew=skew,kurtosis=kurt))
  }#function to calculate mean, standard deviation, skewness and kurtosis.

From the plot, it looks like a normal distribution. Use Kolmogorov-Smirnov test to test the significance.

H0: SalaryPA has the same distribution as normal distribution with mean 119948 and standard deviation 27960.15.

H1: SalaryPA doesnt have the same distribution as normal distribution with mean 119948 and standard deviation 27960.15.

(The original hypothesis and alternative hypothesis of Kolmogorov-Smirnov test below are similar as this one.)

ks.test(jitter(dataPA$SalaryPA),pnorm,mean(dataPA$SalaryPA),sd(dataPA$SalaryPA))
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  jitter(dataPA$SalaryPA)
## D = 0.11629, p-value = 0.05785
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

p-value >0.05, cant reject H0 at 95% confidence interval. SalaryPA follows normal distribution with mean 119948 and standard deviation 27960.15.

The median of residuals is -1590, which is too large! It means there could be excessive error in the regression model.

The adjusted R-squared is 0.4097, which is very small. It means that this regression result could only explain less than 50% of this model.

The p-value of F-statistic to this linear regression model is less than 2.2e-16, so the regression model is very significant.

From coefficients, we can see that there are only 3 variables are significant: rankAsstProf, rankProf and discipline1.

opar <- par(mfrow=c(1,1))
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(fit_all)

1)Residuals vs Fitted: Observations of the error term are obviously uncorrelated with each other.

2)Normal Q-QIf residuals follow standard normal distribution, then they should follow the straight line on the graph. They look good on the plot!

3)Scale-LocationThe variance of the errors should be consistent for all observations; on the graph, the points around the horizontal line should be randomly distributed. They also look good on the plot!

4)Residuals vs LeverageOn this plot, we can see 3 outliers.

Overall, the regression model is good according to those diagnosis graphs.

relweights <-function(fit,...){                       
    R <- cor(fit$model)  
    nvar <- ncol(R)         
    rxx <- R[2:nvar, 2:nvar]
    rxy <- R[2:nvar, 1]     
    svd <- eigen(rxx)       
    evec <- svd$vectors                          
    ev <- svd$values        
    delta <- diag(sqrt(ev)) 
    lambda <- evec %*% delta %*% t(evec)       
    lambdasq <- lambda ^ 2  
    beta <- solve(lambda) %*% rxy          
    rsquare <- colSums(beta ^ 2)                  
    rawwgt <- lambdasq %*% beta ^ 2   
    import <- (rawwgt / rsquare) * 100
    lbls <- names(fit$model[2:nvar])  
    rownames(import) <- lbls
    colnames(import) <- "Weights"
    import
    barplot(t(import),names.arg=lbls,
            ylab="% importance",
            xlab="variables",
            width=0.2,
            cex.axis = 0.8,
            cex.names = 0.6,
            las=2,
            main="Relative Importance of Variables",
            sub=paste("R-Square=", round(rsquare, digits=3)),
            ...) 
    return(import)
}#view the relative importance of each variable

There is a multicollinearity between yrs.since.phd and yrs.service. Their VIFs are near 7, and the multicollinearity cant be ignored. There are two ways to reduce the impact of multicollinearity: stepwise regression and ridge regression.

Backward stepwise regression

Ridge regression

Ridge regression is a method that we dont have to omit any variable and can resolve the multicollinearity problem.

library(ridge)

Performance of each model

performance<-function(table,n=4){
  if(!all(dim(table)==c(2,2)))
    stop("Must be a 2 x 2 table")
  tn=table[1,1]
  fp=table[1,2]
  fn=table[2,1]
  tp=table[2,2]
  sensitivity=tp/(tp+fn)
  specificity=tn/(tn+fp)
  ppp=tp/(tp+fp)
  npp=tn/(tn+fn)
  hitrate=(tp+tn)/(tp+tn+fp+fn)
  result<-paste("Sensitivity=",round(sensitivity,n),
                "\nSpecificity=",round(specificity,n),
                "\nPositive Predictive Value=",round(ppp,n),
                "\nNegative Predicted Value=",round(npp,n),
                "\nAccuracy=",round(hitrate,n),"\n",sep = "")
  cat(result)
}

Data Set Enhancement

Question (1)

Problem 1:

It is weird that years of service/years since PhD was first received is not significant to the linear regression model. However, in the random forest model, yrs.since.phd is the most important variable, and in the classification decision tree model, it is also used to do the classification.

I first thought it is because there is a multicollinearity between yrs.since.phd and yrs.service, but the regression result of keeping one of them is still insignificant.I tried generalized linear model, and the results are excellent: all variables are very significant, but the residuals are not independent of each other.Then I realized that salaries go up at first and down afterward by yrs.since.phd and by yrs.service, hence glm works while lm doesnt.But it still goes against our common sense that salary is positively correlated with working experience.

To resolve it, I think enlarging sample size is necessary, and we can also compare the salaries by yrs.since.phd and by yrs.service in other universities. If they have the same trend of going up and down, then I think generalized linearity model could be good for analysis. If they are different, then we can use larger sample to do another linear regression, and compare two results.

Problem 2:

When I do the second analysis problem, I use Wilcoxon test to see whether there is statistically significant difference between female and male salaries, and the result shows that the statement is true. However, in the predictive models below, sex is the least important variables and make very less contribution to prediction.

The reason I think is that the number of female in this data set is much less than the number of male, which is 39 to 358, so that its impact might be ignored when doing prediction. So the sample size of female salaries must be enlarged to closed to the sample size of male salaries.

Problem 3:

The accuracy of prediction models is too low, which is only around 80%. As I tried using more than 5 different models and all of them dont work very well, so I think the enhancement of data set will contribute more to accuracy than the improvement of models.

Again, enlarging sample size is the first thing. We can use power analysis to find the appropriate sample size.For example, we want to analyze the relationship between sex and salary, and we can see from the correlation matrix that the correlation between sex and salary is -0.1386102. Also, we want a significant level of 95% and a probability of 90% to test it:

library(pwr)
pwr.r.test(r=-0.1386102,sig.level=0.05,power=0.9,alternative="two.side")
## 
##      approximate correlation power calculation (arctangh transformation) 
## 
##               n = 541.9727
##               r = 0.1386102
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9
##     alternative = two.sided

So we need a sample size of 542 people to find out the relationship between sex and salary.

Question (2)

Below are 6 variables I would like to add to the data set for more accurate salary analysis. These variables are based on my interview to a dean of the medical college in China university, since I didnt find too much information about the component and effective factors of teachers salaries in America.

  1. Administrative status: Teachers with administrative status, such as dean of college, department director, discipline leader, will earn higher salaries. Each administrative status is a 0/1 binary indicator, for instance, the indicator has a value of 1 if the teacher is dean of college and 0 otherwise. Since it is common that a department director is also the discipline leader, I wont set this variable to be a categorical variable.

  2. Impact Factor: Teachers who publish papers with high impact factor will earn more salaries. The increasing is non-linear, and the higher IF, the faster salaries growth. It is a categorical variable: IF5 ranked 1, 5<IF10 ranked 2, 10<IF15 ranked 3, 15<IF20 ranked 5, 20<IF25 ranked 6, and IF25 ranked 7.

  3. Position: It is a categorical variable: senior teacher ranked 1, associated senior teacher ranked 2, secondary teacher ranked 3, otherwise ranked 4. In China, the average annual income of senior teachers is 143,600, that of associate senior teachers is 103,300, that of secondary teachers is 83,000, and that of junior teachers is 74,400.

  4. University of graduation: Teachers graduating from top schools in the world will have higher basic salaries than those who are not. It is a categorical variable: Top 10 schools ranked 1, top 30 ranked 2, top 50 ranked 3, and 4 otherwise.

  5. Class hour: It is a numerical variable. Teaching more class hours will bring higher income.

  6. Honor: The income level of teachers with honors is 2.8 times of the average income of ordinary teachers in China. It is a categorical variable: Academician ranked 1, Chang Jiang Scholars ranked 2, Distinguished Young Scholars ranked 3, otherwise ranked 4.

Question (3)

Take linear regression model as example, we can also use power analysis to estimate sample size. After adding 6 variables, we have 12 variables in total, 1 explained variable and 11 explanatory variables. If we want our new regression model only has a deviation of 1000, but in our previous research, the deviation could reach 21530, so the effective size is 0.046, which means new sample size will overlap the previous one by only 4.6%.

pwr.f2.test(u=11,f2=0.046,sig.level=0.05,power=0.90)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 11
##               v = 458.7536
##              f2 = 0.046
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.9

So we need a sample size of 459+11+1=471 people.
